# Learning Logs

# Iteration 1: Fetch and Display

In the first iteration, I focused on connecting to the Open-Meteo API and understanding how the data works. I used fetch() to get the weather data and logged the response in the console to explore the JSON structure.

The API returned data in a nested format, so I had to identify which fields to use, like temperature, wind speed, and humidity. The trickiest part was understanding how to access the correct values from the response.

Once I understood the structure, I displayed the current temperature and a few other details on the page. AI helped me better understand how async/await works and how to handle the API response.

# Iteration 2: Design and Data

In this iteration, I focused on making the dashboard more complete and visually appealing. I added a 3-day forecast and displayed the high and low temperatures for each day.

Since the API returns weather as numeric codes, I created a mapping system to convert those codes into readable descriptions and emojis. This made the data much easier to understand.

I also improved the layout by using a card-style design for the forecast and spacing out the content so it looked more like a real weather app. I made design choices to keep it clean, simple, and easy to read.

# Iteration 3: Interactivity and Polish

In the final iteration, I added an interactive feature that allows users to toggle between Celsius and Fahrenheit. This made the dashboard more useful and gave users control over how they view the data.

I also added a loading state so users see “Loading...” while the data is being fetched, and an error message in case the API fails. This made the app feel more complete and reliable.

While testing, I made sure the app handled edge cases, like switching units multiple times and ensuring the data updates correctly each time.

This iteration helped me understand the importance of user experience. Even small features like unit toggling and loading feedback made the app feel much more polished and realistic.